{"tid":1873944,"cid":5,"subCid":10,"title":"美國海關：有中國遊客違法帶雀鳥屍體‘零食’入境","createTime":"2020-02-11T02:37:33.000Z","updateTime":"2020-02-11T06:54:08.000Z","uid":48083,"like":37,"dislike":150,"uniUserReply":83,"replies":[{"pid":"eb45ca2f7ac6144db2d0535fb6d823642c5670e8","tid":1873944,"uid":48083,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-02-11T02:37:33.000Z","msg":"Dulles CBP Intercepts Dead Birds in Passenger Baggage from China<br />\n<br />\nSTERLING, Va. &ndash; U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) agriculture specialists recently seized a package of tiny dead birds in a passenger&rsquo;s baggage at Washington Dulles International Airport.<br />\n<br />\n<img src=\"https://na.cx/i/2KbFOUy.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fna.cx%2Fi%2F2KbFOUy.jpg&h=5bbde95d&s={SIZE}\" /><img src=\"https://na.cx/i/d444v7T.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fna.cx%2Fi%2Fd444v7T.jpg&h=e8f8a34e&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n<br />\nU.S. Customs and Border Protection agriculture specialists discovered a package of pet food that consisted of dead tiny birds in a traveler&rsquo;s baggage from China January 27, 2020<br />\n<br />\nThe package of pet food from<br />\nChina consisted of tiny dead birds.<br />\n<br />\nThe traveler arrived on a flight from Beijing, China January 27 and was destined to an address in Prince George&rsquo;s County, Maryland. During a baggage examination, CBP agriculture specialists discovered a package with pictures of a cat and dog that the passenger said was cat food. The package contained a bunch of unknown small birds, about 2.5 to 3.5 inches in length.<br />\n<br />\nThe birds from China are prohibited for import due to the potential threat of highly pathogenic avian influenza. The avian products were seized on behalf of U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) and destroyed by incineration, with USDA approval.<br />\n<br />\n &ldquo;These dead birds are prohibited from importation to the United States as unprocessed birds pose a potentially significant disease threat to our nation&rsquo;s poultry industries and more alarmingly to our citizens as potential vectors of avian influenza,&rdquo; said Casey Durst, Director of Field Operations for CBP&rsquo;s Baltimore Field Office. &ldquo;Customs and Border Protection agriculture specialists continue to exercise extraordinary vigilance every day in their fight to protect our nation&rsquo;s agricultural and economic prosperity from invasive pests and animal diseases.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;Customs and Border Protection agriculture specialists protect our nation&rsquo;s agricultural industries from a variety of potential threats every day, including from highly pathogenic animal diseases that threaten our nation&rsquo;s economy,&rdquo; said Casey Durst, Director of Field Operations for CBP&rsquo;s Baltimore Field Office. &ldquo;CBP agriculture specialists continue to exercise extraordinary vigilance in their fight to protect our nation&rsquo;s agriculture and economic prosperity from invasive pests and animal diseases.&rdquo;⋯⋯<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cbp.gov/newsroom/local-media-release/dulles-cbp-intercepts-dead-birds-passenger-baggage-china\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbp.gov%2Fnewsroom%2Flocal-media-release%2Fdulles-cbp-intercepts-dead-birds-passenger-baggage-china&d=u5wkwi0qRaq%2FdbVqa5yG4SHfnck7qU2fF1mVfqY7ZMk%3D&h=f2a5a182\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.cbp.gov/newsroom/local-media-release/dulles-cbp-intercepts-dead-birds-passenger-baggage-china</a>"},{"pid":"3b77419d09cd0826ff6abdddb502035260d91262","tid":1873944,"uid":153781,"like":183,"dislike":3,"score":180,"citedBy":2,"replyTime":"2020-02-11T02:40:06.000Z","msg":"Crazy motherfucker Chinese <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/yipes.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"012afe3f0fe2aa5136e55fb6634f08bd395a8629","tid":1873944,"uid":107653,"like":127,"dislike":4,"score":123,"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"